    "dailyBrief": {
        "brent": 79.4,
        "brentDeltaPct": 4.46,
        "bullets": [
            "BREAKING: Iranian state media and the IRGC claim the Strait of Hormuz is closed, though the US reports vessels are still transiting and disputes any formal closure.",
            "Brent crude surged +4.46% in 24 hours to $79.40 as U.S. strikes on Iran entered a second consecutive night, per FOX 13 Tampa Bay and DW.",
            "The Hormuz Crisis Pressure index hit 90 (extreme), up 4 points in 24 hours, driven by event pressure, while the 30-day Escalation Forecast holds at 61 (high)."
        ],
        "date": "2026-07-13",
        "generatedAt": "2026-07-13T14:52:27.545Z",
        "source": "claude",
        "summary": "The Strait of Hormuz sits at the center of a disputed closure claim that is reshaping carrier posture across the region. Iranian state media and the IRGC have formally declared the strait shut, with Iran simultaneously notifying the IMO of a temporary safe maritime corridor, per IRNA; the US and CENTCOM counter that vessels are still transiting and that no physical closure has been verified, a posture echoed in reporting that ships are moving in secret as strikes continue. The physical transit picture is genuinely contested, and this site maintains a cautious closed posture on carrier guidance without asserting the strait is definitively sealed. PortWatch's most recent published data, covering 2026-07-05, recorded 34 transits against a pre-crisis baseline of 88 per day; separately, a scraper-derived 24-hour arrivals count at Gulf ports registered 348 vessels, a figure using a different methodology that should not be read alongside the PortWatch number as a single data series. Brent crude rose +4.46% to $79.40 as the US launched strikes on Iran for a second straight night, per FOX 13 Tampa Bay, and Trump stated the US would run the strait, per the Financial Times. The site's Crisis Pressure composite reached 90 (extreme), with event pressure as the top driver; the 30-day Escalation Forecast sits at 61 (high), unchanged over 24 hours, with Polymarket closure odds as its leading contributor. The gap between those two index readings reflects a market and analytical community pricing in acute present stress while hedging on whether full escalation is locked in.",
        "transitsToday": 34
    },
